",\"text\":\"**Evaluating testing methods**\\n\\nI need to think about modifying the test to cover public APIs with filters, but there’s a possibility of not getting coverage reports. I’m considering reading through the HttpRequestFactory, but that doesn’t seem right. What if I create a test named documents? It feels awkward without comments. An alternative could be forcing the RequestSpecificationImpl to load in a fresh JVM subprocess. I wonder if using a separate Java process is feasible to collect coverage correctly. Also, could I simulate requests to ensure coverage is achieved?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring testing options**\\n\\nI’ve been told not to run tests, but I can inspect them using a small javap. I can't run the tests myself, but perhaps using jshell might work. The developer advises against compiling or running tests directly, which makes things tricky. I noticed that the new RestAssuredHttpBuilder class expression might not call `$get$$class` due to Groovy's dynamic behavior. However, javap reveals that the callsite target \\\"callConstructor\\\" does receive a Class object. I wonder if the CallSite for the constructor caches the target class.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering adjustments in testing setup**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether using `RestAssured.reset()` might lead to fresh instances of `RequestSpecificationImpl` without static `$class` fields persisting. I might want to replace `HttpServer` with `ServerSocket` for more reliable performance and include details like POST body, path params, and params to fully test class closures, though this might just apply to the main class. Also, adding a filter to inspect requests could help in preventing any bypassing of the `SendRequestFilter`.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering task limitations**\\n\\nThe task asks about \\\"attempt 1 no cover,\\\" and I need to figure out if that’s even possible. It seems I may need to change my approach. I’m wondering if I can find alternatives or possibly specify what’s needed explicitly. I’m eager to clarify the requirements, as it’s crucial to ensure I'm on the right path. Let’s see how best I can tackle this challenge effectively to meet the user's needs!\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "No further supported public-API path appears likely to cover the remaining site.\n\nI verified that the added `RequestSpecificationImplTest` already drives the normal Rest Assured request path through:\n\n- `RestAssured.given()`\n- `RequestSpecificationImpl.get(...)`\n- `SendRequestFilter`\n- real HTTP execution via the internal HTTP stack\n\nThe remaining uncovered site is the Groovy-generated synthetic helper:\n\n```text\nio.restassured.internal.RequestSpecificationImpl.class$(RequestSpecificationImpl.groovy)\njava.lang.Class#forName(java.lang.String)\n```\n\nThat helper is not a library behavior API; it is compiler-generated support for a class literal used around `RestAssuredHttpBuilder`. The request-sending behavior that should reach the surrounding code is already exercised by the dedicated test and by several existing request tests, but the dynamic-access report still does not mark this synthetic `class$` call as covered. Covering it more directly would require one of the prohibited approaches:\n\n- direct reflection / method-handle invocation of the synthetic `class$` method,\n- placing a test in the library’s `io.restassured.internal` package,\n- resetting synthetic static cache fields reflectively,\n- isolated/dynamic class loading of the library classes.\n\nI therefore left the test suite focused on the supported public DSL path and did not add an artificial or prohibited coverage hook.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_091f0c095db143f1016a27235897608193abd501715d3c9084\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 2815, "output": 2870, "cacheRead": 64512, "cacheWrite": 0, "total